IPW4CausalInference

Awol Seid

2025-02-21

Causal effect of HAART use on mortality in HIV-infected patients

Survival data measured in 1200 HIV-infected patients. Start of follow-up is HIV seroconversion. Each row corresponds to a 100 day period of follow-up time. Patients can initiate highly active anti-retroviral therapy (HAART) during follow-up. We will estimate the causal effect of HAART on mortality using this dataset, while adjusting both for possible confounding by CD4 count, and for informative censoring due to the effect of CD4 count on dropout, using IPW. In this example, CD4 count is a time-varying covariate.

library(ipw)
library(survival)

HAART Dataset

data("haartdat")

tempdat_df$selvar <- unlist(lapply(split(tempdat_df$exposure, tempdat_df$id), 
                                function(x) {
                                  if (!is.na(match(1, x))) {
                                    return(c(rep(1, match(1, x)), 
                                             rep(0, length(x) - match(1, x))))
                                    }
                                  else {return(rep(1, length(x)))}
                                  }
                                )
                         )

Treatment Weight

Numerator Model

# Treatment denominator model
den_model <- coxph(Surv(tstart, obs_time, exposure)~sex+age+cd4.sqrt,
               data = data_df, subset = tempdat_df$selvar == 1)
summary(den_model)

Cumulative Baseline Hazard \(H_0(t)\): The accumulated risk over time, defined as: \[H_0(t)=\int_0^th_0(u)du\] is what basehaz() returns, where \(h_0(t)\) is the instantaneous risk of an event occurring at time \(t\).

model=num_model
cum_bh_df <- basehaz(model, centered = TRUE)
cum_bh_df

FUNCTION

get_IPWs=function(data_df) 
{
id=data_df$patient
id[1:15]
tstart=data_df$tstart
tstart[1:15]
obs_time=data_df$fuptime
obs_time[1:15]
exposure=data_df$dropout
exposure[1:15]

tempdat_df <- data.frame(id=id, obs_time=obs_time, exposure = exposure)
tempdat_df[1:15,]
tempdat_df <- tempdat_df[order(tempdat_df$id, tempdat_df$obs_time), ]
tempdat_df[1:15,]



tempdat_df$selvar <- unlist(lapply(split(tempdat_df$exposure, tempdat_df$id), 
                                function(x) {
                                  if (!is.na(match(1, x))) {
                                    return(c(rep(1, match(1, x)), 
                                             rep(0, length(x) - match(1, x))))
                                    }
                                  else {return(rep(1, length(x)))}
                                  }
                                )
                         )

tempdat_df[1:20,]


# Treatment numerator/denominator model
model <- coxph(Surv(tstart, obs_time, exposure)~sex+age+cd4.sqrt,
               data = data_df, subset = tempdat_df$selvar == 1)
summary(model)


bh_df <- basehaz(model, centered = TRUE)
bh_df


bh_df1 <- data.frame(obs_time=bh_df$time, cum_bh=bh_df$hazard)
bh_df1
bh_df1$bh[1] <- bh_df1$cum_bh[1]
bh_df1$bh[1]
bh_df1$bh[2:nrow(bh_df1)] <- diff(bh_df1$cum_bh, 1)
bh_df1
bh_df1$cum_bh <- NULL
bh_df1



obs_time_df <- data.frame(obs_time = sort(unique(tempdat_df$obs_time)))
obs_time_df
temp_df <- merge(obs_time_df, data.frame(obs_time = bh_df$time, 
                                         bh_cum = bh_df$hazard), 
                 by = "obs_time", all.x = TRUE)
temp_df[1:10,]
rm(bh_df)


# I do not understand the purpose of this code

if (is.na(temp_df$bh_cum[temp_df$obs_time == min(unique(tempdat_df$obs_time))])) 
    temp_df$bh_cum[temp_df$obs_time == min(unique(tempdat$obs_time))] <- 0

temp_df$bh_cum <- approx(x = temp_df$obs_time, y = temp_df$bh_cum, 
                         xout = temp_df$obs_time, method = "constant", 
                         rule =2)$y
temp_df$bh_um[1:10]
temp_df[1:10,]


temp_df$bh[1] <- temp_df$bh_cum[1]
temp_df$bh[1]
temp_df$bh[2:nrow(temp_df)] <- diff(temp_df$bh_cum, 1)
temp_df[1:10,]


temp_df$bh_cum <- NULL
temp_df[1:10,]


tempdat_df <- merge(tempdat_df, temp_df, by = "obs_time", all.x = TRUE)
tempdat_df[1:10,]
rm(temp_df)


tempdat_df <- tempdat_df[order(tempdat_df$id, tempdat_df$obs_time), ]
tempdat_df[1:10,]


tempdat_df$risk[tempdat_df$selvar == 1] <- predict(model, type = "risk", centered = TRUE)
tempdat_df[1:10,]
tempdat_df$hazard[tempdat_df$selvar == 1] <- with(tempdat_df[tempdat_df$selvar == 1, ], bh * risk)
tempdat_df[1:20,]


tempdat_df$h_prob[
  with(tempdat_df, selvar == 1 & exposure == 0)
  ] <- with(tempdat_df[
    with(tempdat_df, selvar == 1 & exposure == 0),
    ], exp(-1 * bh * risk))
tempdat_df[1:20,]


tempdat_df$h_prob[
  with(tempdat_df, selvar == 1 & exposure == 1)
  ] <- 1 - with(tempdat_df[
    with(tempdat_df, selvar == 1 & exposure == 1), ],
    exp(-1 * bh * risk))
tempdat_df[1:20,]


tempdat_df$h_prob[tempdat_df$selvar == 0] <- 1
tempdat_df[1:20, ]


tempdat_df$cum_prod_prob <- unsplit(lapply(split(tempdat_df$h_prob, tempdat_df$id), function(x) cumprod(x)), tempdat_df$id)
tempdat_df[1:20,]

return(tempdat_df$cum_prod_prob)
}

Causal effect of tuberculosis on mortality in HIV-infected patients

Our third example is similar to the previous example but with measurements made at irregular intervals of follow-up time. We estimate the causal effect of active tuberculosis (TB) on mortality in HIV-positive individuals, adjusted for possible confounding by time-varying CD4 count using IPW. We smooth time-varying CD4 using a random effects model, because it is the underlying “true” CD4, separate from short-term fluctuations and measurement error, that is a confounder for the effect of TB. The simulated datasets basdat and timedat are used in this example. \

Dataset basdat contains time-fixed variables, measured in 386 HIV-positive individuals: id is the patient ID, Ttb is the time of first active tuberculosis, measured in days since HIV seroconversion, Tdeath is the time of death, measured in days since HIV seroconversion, Tend is the individual end time (either death or censoring), measured in days since HIV seroconversion.

Time-fixed data

Dataset timedat contains longitudinal measurements made in the same 386 HIV-positive individuals as basdat: id is the patient ID, fuptime is follow-up time, in days since HIV seroconversion, cd4count is CD4 count, measured at fuptime.

Note that these data were simulated by the authors using the algorithm described in Van der Wal, Prins, Lumbreras, and Geskus (2009). Therefore, CD4 count at a certain time point is affected by the TB status right before that time point. TB status at a certain time point is affected by CD4 count at that specific time point.

Some processing of the original data is necessary. We check if there is more than one CD4 measurement taken on the same day within each patient:

table(duplicated(tvdata_df[, c("id", "fuptime")]))
## 
## FALSE 
##  6291

which is not the case. Because of skewness, we compute the square root of CD4 count:

tvdata_df$cd4.sqrt <- sqrt(tvdata_df$cd4count)
summary(tvdata_df$cd4count)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0   230.0   350.0   357.9   472.0  1154.0
summary(tvdata_df$cd4.sqrt)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00   15.17   18.71   18.24   21.73   33.97

Add the time of first active TB to timedat, and compute tb.lag, the time-varying TB status one day before the measurement time (which is necessary for reasons that are explained below):

merged_df <- merge(tvdata_df, tfdata_df[,c("id","Ttb")], by = "id", all.x = TRUE)

To be able to impute CD4 count at time points other than the measurement times, which is necessary when fitting the MSM (see below), and to smooth the original measurements, we fit the random effects model \[\sqrt{L_i(t)}=\alpha_{1i}+\alpha_{1i}t+\beta_2A_i(t-1)\] with \(t\) follow-up time (days since HIV seroconversion), \(L(t)\) CD4 count, and \(A(t)\) time-varying TB status. Random effects \(\alpha_{1i}\) and \(\alpha_{2i}\) are assumed to be normally distributed with mean \(\bm{\beta}'=(\beta_0,\beta_1)\)) and covariance matrix \(\Sigma\). The model includes a fixed effect for TB, \(\beta_2\). Because CD4 is affected by the TB status right before \(t\), we include \(A(t − 1)\), the TB status one day before \(t\) in the above equation. We can fit the model using:

library(nlme)
cd4.lme <- lme(cd4.sqrt ~ fuptime + tb.lag, random = ~ fuptime | id, data = merged_df)
summary(cd4.lme)
## Linear mixed-effects model fit by REML
##   Data: merged_df 
##        AIC      BIC    logLik
##   13669.72 13716.94 -6827.858
##

We will construct a new dataframe startstop, which will be used to estimate inverse probability weights and to fit an MSM, to quantify the causal effect of TB on mortality. Let \(\bm{T}_{TB}\) be all time points at which the TB-status switches, in any individual. Let \(T\) end be all individual end times. Then, to (1) be able to compute inverse probability weights using a Cox proportional hazards model and (2) be able to fit the MSM, the dataframe startstop should contain, for each individual, rows corresponding to both \(\bm{T}_{TB}\) and \(\bm{T}_{end}\). For each individual we include these time points only up to his or her individual end time. We also sort the time points chronologically within each individual. The dataframe construction is done as follows:

times <- sort(unique(c(tfdata_df$Ttb, tfdata_df$Tend)))
times[1:20]
##  [1]  19  56  67  93 105 116 117 119 155 161 169 190 197 203 204 221 237 253 271
## [20] 302
startstop_df <- data.frame(id = rep(tfdata_df$id, each = length(times)), 
                        fuptime = rep(times, nrow(tfdata_df)))
startstop_df[1:20,]
##    id fuptime
## 1   1      19
## 2   1      56
## 3   1      67
## 4   1      93
## 5   1     105
## 6   1     116
## 7   1     117
## 8   1     119
## 9   1     155
## 10  1     161
## 11  1     169
## 12  1     190
## 13  1     197
## 14  1     203
## 15  1     204
## 16  1     221
## 17  1     237
## 18  1     253
## 19  1     271
## 20  1     302
startstop_df <- merge(startstop_df, tfdata_df, by = "id", all.x = TRUE)

We compute the starting time for each interval of follow-up using tstartfun:

tstartfun <- function(df) {
  tstart_list <- lapply(split(df, df$id), function(subdf) {
    keep <- rep(TRUE, nrow(subdf))
    if(nrow(subdf) > 1) {
      for(i in 2:nrow(subdf)) {
        if(subdf$fuptime[i] <= subdf$fuptime[i - 1]) {
          keep[i] <- FALSE
        }
      }
    }
    subdf <- subdf[keep, ]
    tstart <- c(0, head(subdf$fuptime, -1))
    return(tstart)
  })
  return(unlist(tstart_list))
}
startstop_df$tstart=tstartfun(startstop_df)

Then we compute tb, the TB status at each time point for each individual, and tb.lag, the time-varying TB status one day before each time point for each individual. We also compute event, an indicator for death, and impute time-varying CD4 count cd4.sqrt, using the LME model:

startstop_df$tb <- ifelse(with(startstop_df, !is.na(Ttb) & fuptime >= Ttb), 1, 0)
startstop_df$tb.lag <- ifelse(with(startstop_df, !is.na(Ttb) & fuptime > Ttb), 1, 0)
startstop_df$event <- ifelse(with(startstop_df, !is.na(Tdeath) & fuptime >= Tdeath), 1, 0)
startstop_df$cd4.sqrt <- predict(cd4.lme, 
                              newdata = data.frame(id = startstop_df$id,
                                                   fuptime = startstop_df$fuptime, 
                                                   tb.lag = startstop_df$tb.lag))

Note that for each row in startstop, cd4.sqrt contains imputed CD4 count that predicts tb in the same row. To correct for confounding by time-varying CD4 count, we can estimate the stabilized inverse probability weights: \[w_{it}\]
